It appears from the epitome of Gaius, contai ned in the laws of the Visigoths (Breviarium Alarici), that Gaius proceeded to men- tion two modes of verbal obligation without previous interrogation, the dotis dictio, and the jurata promissio liberti. Dotis dictio was the declaration of a wife, or her father, or her debtor, settling a dotal estate, movable or immovable, on the husband. J urata pro- missio liberti was the sworn promise of a freedman, immediately after his manumission, to render certain services (operae) to his patron. It was usual to bind the conscience of the slave ΒΥ a similar promise before manumission3 but such a promise had no legal operation.
